segments.text: So I said, you just go ahead and plan on making $10,000 worth of these one burner stoves.
And I don't care how many it is, but give us a fair shake on it.
He said, well, we'll do that.
Well, hell, in about two weeks, he said, well, it looks like we're going to be able to make paying for the die costs and some other costs
we'll be able to have for you about 360 or something like that for the $10,000.
And he said additional stones after that would be, I think, $7 or $8 or $9 a piece, something like that, on a negotiated basis.
So I told the boss about it and told Colonel Moss about it, and he said, oh, that's fine, that's fine.
Well, then I pulled a little shenanigans.
I convinced the guys to write into the G4 annex for the landings in North Africa that every armored vehicle and every armored personnel carrier and every command car
have one of these one-burner gasoline stoves for provision of providing hot rations for the troops.
Well, after they figured out what that would amount to based upon the T-O and E of the units that were scheduled for the North African operation, it amounted to some 10,000 odd units.
And to make a long story short, it wasn't very long after that we got the authority to go ahead and buy that many plus some more for maintenance and follow on and so forth.
And you've been a friend of the Coleman's ever since.
And then after that, why, the one burner stove was this, about that time Ernie Pyle, the reporter, was in North Africa.
He mentioned in one of his stories about this one burner stove.
Sheldon Coleman called me on the phone.
He said, say, Ernie Pyle has mentioned about your one burner stove.
He always referred to it as your one burner stove.
And I said, yeah.
Somebody told me.
I didn't see the article.
He said the employees in the factory would like to send him one, specially made stainless steel with his name engraved on it and everything.
Can you get it to him?
And I said, well, I'm pretty sure I can.
So they did.
A beautiful one-burner stone, exact facsimile, all fancied up with stainless steel engraved and everything.
And I got it over to him.
thanking me for.
And he said, it's so pretty that I'll never use it.
I'll always just use one that I can, a regular GI stove that I can use.
And when he was killed in the Pacific, we looked and looked and looked to try to find that stove.
But because the Coleman Company wanted to put it on exhibit out there perpetually.
But we never, we never found it.
We contacted the unit that he was with.
And I don't know what happened to it.
Somebody's got it somewhere.
But anyway, the little one burner stove is really the, I got a great personal satisfaction out of that little thing.
Because it served a great purpose.
And really, really was really a helpmate to a lot of people.
And I got, as a result, like you say, I was very friendly with Coleman.
And they wanted me after the war.
They offered me a hell of a fine job to go to their Canadian operation in Montreal.
And I was to be the number two man then.
And they said that the number one man was scheduled to retire in about three years,
But I didn't do it.
I went in the service, the regular service.
And Sheldon, it kind of upset him that I didn't take it because he had paved a lot of streets and paved a lot of way for me to come in at that level.
But we're still friends and good friends about it.
But it was something that we gave birth to, and everybody was against it because we don't have a requirement for it.
And nobody wanted to stick their neck out and say, let's accept.
We finally convinced a couple of the powers that be at that time to go along with it.
What other types of projects did

Right about that, a little after that too, and I've got a patent on that, we, in the shipment of gasoline for invasion and for follow-on, the gasoline, we need, not in the shipment, but in the handling of gasoline in the field, even with a pipeline operation,
There's a great military necessity for the five gallon can, jerry can.
Well, shipping those five gallon gasoline cans, and we also had five gallon cans to carry water, but the big requirement was for gasoline cans, five gallon gasoline cans.
And as some of our petroleum pipeline distribution companies

we would have what we call decanting operations where at the terminal, at the pipeline, they would have thousands of cans that would be filled and units would come up and pick up a truckload full of filled cans and then bring in a truckload of empty cans.
So, shipping those cans overseas was quite a logistic thing because

what you're doing is shipping a ship full of air because you've got empty cans and early in the day a lot of people said, well why don't we fill them with some kind of dry subsistence, what kind of subsistence?
Beans or something like that and it never was very feasible to do that.
So I got the idea, let's ship the cans knocked down but nested.
In other words, ship a can that was almost complete except for one side, put a slight slant on the sides of the can so you could nest them.
And then the end, the top or the end, you could stack them up.
And then overseas, one of the ordinance companies could set up a line, a welding line, and they could assemble the finished cans.
Drop in the closure, have that all in one piece, so just drop it in and spot weld it.
The handle would already be on it.
No, the handle you could spot weld it on.
And the body of the can would be nested, stacked up.
And he then just put the top on them and run a bead weld around it.
And they already had automatic, a little simple field expedient machine that could run a bead weld around it.
So the idea was so good that the military patented the thing in my name for their exclusive use.
And for any commercial use after the military didn't want it, it would become my property.
So a patent was issued and everything for this nested gasoline can.
Several million were procured.
and shipped overseas and assembled just like we envisioned.
And then after the war some were sold surplus and there were some produced after the war that I was supposed to have gotten a royalty on but I never did get it.
One of the companies that made them
I, at that time, I wasn't really interested in spending a lot of money legally to try to get a few pennies of can out of it.
But anyway, I got a lot of satisfaction out of it, this nested can.
The only other real projects that I was involved in, which have kind of carried over into civilian life after the war,

I was particularly interested and involved in aviation fuel safety, as far as the military is concerned, and wrote some of the early comprehensive handbooks and manuals on military aviation fuel safety, particularly as it applies to jet fuel, turbine fuel.
because turbine fuel is sort of a morphidite.
It's not a gasoline and it's not a kerosene.
It's a mixture of both.
And military jet fuel in the early days and even today is a very dangerous jet fuel in that
at all ambient temperatures found on Earth, and even up to 50,000, 60,000 feet, the vapors from JP4, which is military jet fuel, are always in the explosive range.
And military jet fuel has an almost unknown, un-understood

characteristic of the generation of static electricity that nobody knows why it generates so much static electricity when it flows, when you pump it or when you transfer it or even when you pour it out of a can.
The molecules in military jet fuel bumping one against the other and flowing when you pump them through a pipeline or pump them into a tank.
have the characteristic to generate static electricity in pretty high, pretty high amounts, pretty high voltage amounts.
Which means the possibility of fires?
The possibility of explosion and fire.
And the only way to prevent it is to properly ground both the refueling unit and the unit being refueled.
Ground them to a common bond.
So we alerted and helped alert a lot of military usage of the safety and the handling of jet fuel.
I then became, in the 60s, early 60s, became involved with a civilian organization.
known as the Airways Club.
It was headquartered in New York at that time.
It's now headquartered in Dallas and known as the Airline Passengers Association.
It started out and still is a source of permanent airline insurance.
You can buy airline insurance from Airline Passengers Association.
Instead of buying an individual policy each time,
But anyway, they ran a newsletter about airline safety.

And I made a comment to them one time about the use of jet fuel in commercial airlines, the use of military jet fuel in commercial airliners, which they published in their newsletter and got pretty wide distribution.
It caused quite a furor in civilian aviation.
And a lot of people said that I was just throwing up smoke screens to scare people and so forth.
What did it say?
I said that the use of military jet fuel in commercial airliners was a very, very dangerous practice.
And that there was the possibility of in-flight explosion and destruction of the aircraft.
Well, I'm sorry to say that's exactly what happened in 1961, a Pan Am 707 returning from San Juan to Philadelphia at an interim stop at Friendship Airport in Baltimore.
It had been refueled in San Juan with JP4.
It flew to Friendship Airport in Baltimore and stopped
And they did not top off the main tank.
The main tank was about half full.
All the tanks were full when they left San Juan with JP4.
They did not top off the main tank, which was about half empty, nor did they top off any of the wing tanks.
The wing tanks had been drawn down equally to keep the trim on.
Both of the wing tanks were about half full and of course the wing tanks have a vent to the outside.
The main tank was about half full because they only had a short distance to fly then from Baltimore to Philadelphia.
They took off from Philadelphia with all of the tanks partially full.
And they encountered very, very severe turbulence and a very severe electrical storm.
And just a few minutes out of Baltimore, over Elkton, Maryland, a lightning struck the aircraft and ignited vapors coming out of one of the vents.
I think it was a left wing tank.
Ignited, and then through some faulty
arrangement of the vent or faulty functioning of the vent valves, the fire and explosion fed back into the tank and exploded the left wing tank and destroyed the airplane.
Seventy, I think sixty some odd people were killed.
The FAA picked up the pieces from the early description.
It sounded like there was an in-flight explosion.
The FAA picked up the pieces of this airplane and put them in the hangar in Bowling Field in Washington so they could be examined.
That's what they do today in a crash is pick up all the pieces like a jigsaw puzzle.
And it was very plain what had happened because the wing tanks were blown out and the skin and everything was peeled back.
So it ignited and fire fed into the main tank.
And this proved, this was a living proof of some of the theories that had been set forth about the possibility and the hazards with military jet fuel.
So after Elkton, some of the airlines stopped using military jet fuel.
Now, they used military jet fuel whenever they could.
for several reasons.
Number one, the biggest reason, it was cheaper.
It was much cheaper than a Jet A or Jet A-1, which were the civilian jet fuels.
You're immediately gonna say, well, why isn't the military jet fuel as safe as the civilian jet fuel?
The answer is, at that time, and I think it's still true today,
military jet fuel is very easy to make, very simple to make.
And it's very easy to make in the large quantities that the military would require, or that the military air forces in the free world would require to fight a world war.
Whereas Jet A and Jet A-1, which are really and truly aviation kerosene,
are more expensive and we can make less of them.
Out of every barrel of crude oil, we can probably make about 20 gallons of military jet fuel.
Whereas out of every barrel of crude oil, we can probably only make about seven gallons of civilian jet fuel because of the mix of the fractions that go into it.
Military jet fuel is so easy to make.
You can take some of the diesel elements and some of the gasoline elements in storage tanks at refineries and blend them as they load a tanker.
They actually make military jet fuel while they're loading the tanker.
Pump out of this tank, pump out of this tank, pump out of this tank.
The few additives they put in, such as anti-corrosive and anti-water additives, add them in.
And it's all dumped into the tank and the holes of the tanker and becomes military jet fuel, JP-4.
It's very easy to make.
I know my son at Fort McPherson in a science project, a science fair project, I had him make military jet fuel.
And he made it in the house there, and I got him all the little fractions, and he made it into fair.
And he showed them how I would test them.

So I was much involved in that in civilian life and even some of it spilled over in the military when I said one day that MATS, Military Air Transport Service, should not fly dependents in 707s that had JP-4 in them.
And finally I said that the White House fleet
to haul the president around and all the VIPs.
One day, I got an anonymous call and did a briefing in the Pentagon one day.
General LeMay said, who in the hell is this guy Kinderdine to tell us what kind of fuel we ought to use?
But I got an anonymous call one day.
This was before I retired.
yeah this was in 65 or 66.
And they said you'd be very interested to know that the order was given this morning that Air Force One and all aircraft in the VIP fleet at Andrews henceforth would not use JP-4 anymore.
So I told the Airways Club about it.
I called New York and told them.
I said, well, the military is starting to break now on this thing.
And they called the White House.
The Airways Club called the White House and wanted confirmation of this rumor that was floating around that Air Force One and all of the VIP fleet would henceforth
not use military jet fuel anymore for safety purposes.
And they refused to confirm it.
They refused to confirm or deny it.
They said, we can do neither.
But in about a week, there was a little announcement in the paper that they're going to use it.
Well, anyway, they've changed the specs a little bit for military jet fuel.
It's a little bit safer now, but it
We've lost a lot of aircraft in the military.
Where you've read aircraft exploded shortly after takeoff or something like that because of the volatility of JP-4.
Now in your Vita, it says that you worked on several projects with the Alaskan and the European theaters.

And some of the projects in European theater during the war, the only, well after the war I did some special work in the European theater on special purpose facilities which included underground facilities and the like that I probably should not comment on.
and even within connection with some of our allies.
But I during the war then and in my my I was assigned to service forces and did some duty with the Third Army with Patton's group and not long enough for my own satisfaction and
Then I was back over in Europe.
I came home in late 45 and then went back over there during the occupation in Germany.
Okay, but were you stationed in Europe or were you stationed in Washington?
I was stationed in Washington.
Throughout the whole war you were in Washington.
Most of the time I was assigned in Washington.
And what you were doing was helping them lay the pipe, basically?
No, I had nothing to do with that.
No, this was all in...
These were different.
This was all in logistic and planning and operational things.
Mostly, well I did this before the Normandy landings, I did a lot of work in the
and the G4 annex of the landings in Normandy.
And then after that, I was in on several projects in Europe.
I was never assigned to a specific like the umpty umpt army or the umpty umpt brigade.
I was always assigned in a staff to the headquarters third army or headquarters service forces Europe or something like that.
After the war, I was back over in Europe during the occupation.
And then while I was there during the occupation, the Berlin Airlift came along.
Yeah, in 1948.
Yeah, and I was very, very much involved in the Berlin Airlift.
Okay, but before we get to the Berlin Airlift, which I certainly want you to talk about because it's so important.
How about right after the war was over, did you think at that time
Now you might go back to civilian life, or did you, by that time, did you made up your mind that you wanted to be a career officer?
I had not positively made up my mind that I wanted to be a career officer because I had this opportunity to go to work for the Coleman Company.
What rank were you at that time?
I was a full colonel.
I was a full colonel.
I got my Eagles after VE day.
In fact, they were pinned on me in Paris under the Arc de Triomphe by some of my buddies, yeah.
I was not, I had not made up my mind that I wanted to become a career officer because I had this this Coleman thing.
I had the possibility of another job with
this big industrialist Ludwig, you may have heard of.
He owns most of the tankers in the world today.
Has extensive operations in South America, in mining and offices in New York.
One of my buddies went to work for him.
I could have gone to work for him and I could have also
I'm pretty sure I could have gone to work for the General American Transportation Company that operates most of the tank cars in the United States, that owns most of the tank cars.
What about going back to West Texas and getting back into the oil field?
I thought about that too, but the oil business just kind of moved so fast during the war
and the technology and everything just had quantum jumps.

I could have gone back to Norville Wilder, the supply house, because Lipp Norville came to Washington and said that he wanted me to come back here to the Fort Worth office or to their office in Shreveport.
So I, but very quickly after the war, I made the decision, I think I'll put in for the Regner Army, because they announced the integration program.
Why did you make that decision?
What was it about the military that was so attractive, even though you had a number of excellent job offers?
Yeah, I don't know.
I had a lot of success during the war, a lot of personal satisfaction.
I had personal satisfaction and personal success that very few people, very few of my peers were able to, I think, experience as much of as I did.
And it just kind of got me.
I just liked it.
And I knew that a peacetime army or that a post-war time army, the activities would be grossly different from what they were during wartime.
But I felt that I could adapt to it.
And I don't really know.
My folks, my wife liked the service.
What did she like about it?
I think she liked the variety about it.
You know, you stay at a place two or three years and then you go for something else.
We moved 22 times.
And she liked that.
And my kids liked it.
They liked the going places and meeting new friends and new people.
My daughter went to three high schools.
She would have gone to four, but we left her in Paris to graduate after we came home.
I think they were, I think my family was more or less motivated and challenged by military life.
And I think particularly my son, he too wanted to study military history.
And he wanted to teach military history.
He went to Duke and went there through his junior year.
And I said, look, what the hell can you do after you graduate except maybe work for Hanson Baldwin or somebody like that?
And I said, why don't you get in the business school?
I said, I know Art Weimer out in Indiana.
And he's the dean of the School of Business.
And I believe you can transfer out there.
And he hadn't done too well at Duke.
He's a real good student.
And I said, you can transfer out there.
And he got in a little trouble down at Duke.
And I said, why don't you just check into them and go on out to Indiana this summer and go to summer school and maybe you can catch up and you'll be right even with your class then.
So he did.
We drove out there.
He went to summer school and he was 4-0 in summer school.
He carried a real heavy load and he did real well.
But I think they were motivated by the service, even though they were just youngsters right after the war.
But they liked the military, and my wife liked it.
So I made the decision and took my board, my regular Army integration board in San Antonio, Fort Sam Houston.
Were you fearful right after the war that you might be demoted
except those that had attained permanent rank, and most of them were just about ready to retire.
So I was demoted to a lieutenant colonel when I was integrated.
Matter of fact, about a month before I was integrated, and there was several thousand on the same demotion list.
And I was a lieutenant colonel for, I guess, about five years then before I became a colonel.
Was that demoralizing in any way?
No, no, it wasn't then.
No, not at all.
It was, you know, it's something that you understand in time of war with a large force structure and why the higher ranks are filled by rapid promotion during the war.
You could be promoted every six months.
Sure.
some occasions promotions were quicker, but normally every six months you were promoted, almost like clockwork.
And it was an expected thing, and so there was no problem at all to

So, and I look back many times on this thing, and I know many times, you know, nostalgia, you think about, well, I suppose he would have gone back in the oil business, might be a multi-millionaire today, because some of the guys that you worked with or started out with made it big.
But I think when you weigh everything, the personal satisfaction and the
joy and the feeling of accomplishment that you get.
I really believe that if I had the decision to make again today, I'd do the same thing.
I really believe I would.
Let's talk now about the Berlin Arrow left.
Tell me about it.
Okay.
Well, I think here again, I've been awful lucky in my military career.
At this time, you were director of supply?
I was director of supply of the largest depot in the European theater of operations.
Where was that in Germany?
It's in Gieen, Germany.
It's not that now.
It was then.
It's in Gieen, which is about 40 miles north of Frankfurt, off the Autobahn, right off the Autobahn.
The G-I-E-S-S-E-N, Gieen, Gieen.
And it was a German airfield, big German airfield that we built this depot on.
It was kind of like a saucer.
And the airfield was down in the bottom of the saucer.
And of course, when it rained, the water, we had water and mud in the depot.
And I lived in the commanding officer, the German commanding officer's house, a nice big stucco house right in front of the gate to the airfield.
And like I say, I was lucky.
Here's a case where I guess I was at the right place at the right time.
Because things were going from bad to worse.
Would you like a drink or a Coke or something?
Yeah, I would.
Let me get that.
You want a Coke or what?
In the airlift.
Yeah, let's continue with the airlift.
Like I say, me personally, my personal, I was just a lucky guy.
I was at the right place at the right time.
I got a call in my office from Heidelberg, the headquarters of the U.S. Army Europe, about 1 o'clock, right after lunch, telling me to...
go down to Ryan Main Airport in Frankfurt, Air Base in Frankfurt, and represent the Army at a meeting that was going to be presided over by General LeMay.
I think he was head of the Air Force in Europe.
And of course, the tensions had been getting stronger and stronger over access to Berlin.
The Russians had threatened and had closed the Autobahn
and the only thing that was open was the rail line into Berlin and the air corridor into Berlin.
So I asked, I think it was the G-4 officer, maybe it was the G-4 of the command, I asked him what the nature was and he said, well I'm not real sure, but it's a classified

subject, it's a classified meeting and he said you just better go ahead and you're representing the army and he said if there's anything real controversial that you don't feel competent to handle, give me a ring and I said okay, so I went and I got down there just as quick as I could, about 40 miles, took me about an hour to get out there and

General LeMay opened a thing by saying that General Clay, who was the Supreme Commander then, had been contacted by the Joint Chiefs and by the White House and was told to be prepared to start sending aircraft into Berlin with supplies for Berlin, for everybody in Berlin,
And that the Air Corps, the Air Force, it was the Air Force by the end, the Air Force had already ordered additional transport aircraft to come to Germany.
There were some that were going to start later that evening from as far away as Alaska, some four-engine C-54s.
Some were coming from Gwilas in North Africa, and some were coming from England,
And even they were going to use a few C-47 twin-engine, but he hoped to use only four-engine aircraft.
And he said, the Army is represented.
And he said, where is the Army?
I had introduced myself to him when I came in and told him I was a G-4, asked me to represent the Army.
And he said, it's going to fall upon the Army to furnish the cargo.
to fill these airplanes up this first day.
And he asked me, he said, how much cargo can you give me?
And I said, well, General LeMay, how much would you like to have?
And that kind of put the ball back at him.
And he said, well, he said, for the first day, I'd like to have at least 500 tons.
Because I'm going to have all my four-engine aircraft
I'll be able to put about eight to nine tons gross in those four-engine C-54s.
And depending upon what it is, the cube and so forth of it, he said, I'm hoping that
And then, of course, we'll need more cargo each day thereafter.
But he said, tonight, I'd like to have enough to load what aircraft that we think we're going to be able to initiate the airlift with.
And I said, well, do you have any idea
And I said, you have no desires or no requirement or no specification of what you want to fly.
He said, we'll leave that up to you.
So I said, fine.
Now, he said, well, how much can you give me?
And I said, General LeMay, I will lay down on this airfield tonight for you, by midnight, 500 tons of cargo.
He said, that's good enough.
So I said, if I may be excused, I'm
to my command.
So I called Heidelberg and told them.
And they said, well can you do it?
I said, yeah, it'd be no problem at all.
They said, well what you gonna ship?
And I said, well I haven't really crystallized, but you know, I think I'll ship the ingredients to make bread.
Because the easiest goddamn stuff to load.
We can ship a balanced requirement.
Canned milk and yeast and flour and sugar and
And there's even in the military ration, once a week, they bake raisin bread.
And of course, I didn't mention that.
But what I'm going to tell you in a minute or two will bear that out.
So I called.
And after, they said, that's fine.
And they said, god damn, be sure you get it there at least by 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning.
I said, it'll be here by midnight.
So I hung up.
chief of operations to stand by and I didn't know what the hell was going to come out of this meeting.

So they were all waiting for me and I said well we need 500 tons and I said I want you to make a run on the on the IBM and get the tonnage and get all the all the print out on the just divide it up and let's shift 500 tons of all the ingredients to bake
the military bread program.
And they said, what?
And I said, make bread.
All the ingredients to make bread.
They said, well, that's a cinch.
I said, I know it is.
And I said, you better have all those DP companies.
Well, we used three or four companies of displaced persons as laborers in the depot there.
It was so big.
Still as late as 48?
Yeah.
Really?
There were still DP's hanging around?
We had several thousand DP's, Poles and Czechs, that hadn't gone back.
Not any Russians?
No, we didn't have any Russians.
We had some Poles and DP's.
And they didn't want to go back?
I don't think they wanted to go back.
Most of them were involved in the black market and shacked up with Frauleins and everything.
But were they working for you, or were they working for us as labor units?
And were they on payroll?
Yeah.
They were living in a quasi-military surrounding, but working for us and making a monthly wage as labor troops.
And I said, better alert several of those truck companies in Geesen.
We had a dozen or so truck companies that were all black truck companies.
